      "note": "According to Tabari, the noun fann (lit., \"mode\" or \"manner\") is in this case synonymous with lawn (\"colour\" or \"hue\"). Afnan is a double plural, and hence denotes \"many hues\"; and since - as pointed out in the Taj al-'Arus - one of the several accepted meanings of fann is \"a wonderful thing\", afnan can also be understood as many wonderful things\". The rendering adopted by me combines both these interpretations. - As regards the indescribable nature of what is termed \"paradise\", see 32:17 and the corresponding note 15."
